Step 3 — Real-World Cross-Check
Based on training data benchmarks: Enterprise software and B2B enterprise sales typically carry gross margins of 60–80%, and even enterprise hardware/product businesses target 40–60% gross margin. A segment running at −3.1% gross margin in any industry would be treated as a business emergency. The pattern observed here — where discounting erodes a razor-thin unit margin to the point of systematic loss — is consistent with what happens when enterprise contracts are structured without reference to product-level cost profiles. Industry playbooks (McKinsey, Bain) consistently flag "one-size pricing for multi-cost products" as a leading cause of enterprise segment under-performance in B2B sales organizations.

Step 4 — The Setup
Enterprise is the only segment destroying value — and current reporting hides it.
Every other segment is profitable. Government earns 21.7% margins on $52.5M in revenue. Small Business generates $4.1M in profit. Channel Partners runs at 73% gross margin. Midmarket contributes positively. Enterprise alone posts a $614,546 operating loss on $19.6M in revenue — a −3.1% margin. But that reported loss understates reality. The COGS calculation uses a flat $120/unit rate for all Enterprise transactions. For two products — Amarilla (manufacturing cost: $260) and VTT (manufacturing cost: $250) — Enterprise is selling units at $125 while the actual cost to produce them is $260 and $250 respectively. The reporting system does not catch this because it never charges actual manufacturing cost to Enterprise COGS. Strip that out and the true loss on those two products alone exceeds $5.5M.

Step 5 — S→C→R Narrative
Situation: The business is healthy overall, generating $16.9M in profit on $118.7M in revenue — a 14.2% blended margin. Government and Small Business are the profit engines, each delivering strong absolute returns. The company has pricing discipline: every segment has a distinct sale price point calibrated to its customer type and margin profile.
Complication: Enterprise is the exception. It operates with a single flat sale price of $125/unit across all six products — regardless of whether the product costs $3 to make (Carretera) or $260 (Amarilla). The system then calculates Enterprise COGS at a fixed $120/unit, giving the appearance of a $5/unit gross margin. At zero discount, that margin holds. But the moment any discount is applied — and 94% of Enterprise transactions carry some discount — that $5 evaporates. At the Medium band (6.8% discount), Enterprise loses $3.53 per unit. At the High band (12.4% discount), it loses $10.44 per unit. Across 33 High-discount transactions representing $6.5M in revenue, the segment loses $622K. This is not a discount problem in isolation — it is a pricing logic failure that made the segment fundamentally loss-making the moment discounts entered the picture.
The deeper problem is that for Amarilla and VTT — two products with manufacturing costs of $260 and $250 — Enterprise is selling at $125, meaning it is selling below manufacturing cost on every single transaction for those SKUs. The COGS system masks this by applying $120 flat, so the P&L never flags it. The true loss on Amarilla alone, using actual manufacturing costs, is −$3.3M. On VTT, it is −$2.7M. Together: −$5.99M in true economic loss on those two products.
Resolution: This pattern is a textbook case of "product-agnostic enterprise pricing" — where a single contract rate is applied to a multi-SKU catalog without cost segmentation. The fix requires two parallel actions: (1) immediate suspension or repricing of Amarilla and VTT in Enterprise contracts (these products should never have been offered at $125 when they cost $250–$260 to produce), and (2) a discount governance framework that sets a floor margin below which no Enterprise deal can be approved. Companies that have navigated this successfully (per established B2B sales literature) implement deal-level profitability gates enforced by finance before contract execution.
Why leadership should care: Enterprise represents 16.5% of total revenue. It is not a rounding error — it is a meaningful book of business that is actively subsidized by every other segment. Left unaddressed for another 12 months, the cumulative loss trajectory suggests $1.2M–$1.5M in additional losses based on 2013→2014 run rate. More importantly, the COGS reporting error means leadership has been making resource and investment decisions based on a materially incorrect view of this segment's economics.

Step 6 — Engineered Variables
Three new variables created for this analysis:
True COGS = Units Sold × Manufacturing Price (actual per-product cost, vs. the flat $120 applied in source data).
Formula: TRUE_COGS = [Units Sold] * [Manufacturing Price]
Why: Exposes the real economic cost of each transaction. Without this, Amarilla and VTT losses are invisible.
True Profit = Sales − True COGS
Formula: TRUE_PROFIT = [Sales] - TRUE_COGS
Why: Reveals the actual P&L impact, especially for high-cost products sold at Enterprise's flat $125 price.
Margin per Unit = Profit / Units Sold
Formula: MARGIN_PER_UNIT = [Profit] / [Units Sold]
Why: Makes the discount erosion visible at the unit level — $5.00 at None, $1.93 at Low, −$3.53 at Medium, −$10.44 at High.
Discount Rate Actual = Discounts / Gross Sales
Why: Benchmarks actual discount rates by band. Confirms Medium ≈ 6.8%, High ≈ 12.4%.

Step 7 — DAX Measures
dax-- Total Sales (net revenue after discounts)
Total Sales = SUM('Financials'[Sales])

-- Total Profit (as reported)
Total Profit = SUM('Financials'[Profit])

-- Gross Margin % (reported)
